The ruler trick has nothing to do with shutter speed. It can be seen without a camera, granted you have the correct setup. I stumbled upon this when I started playing guitar some 10 or so years ago. I have a 59Hz monitor which is usually the only lightsource when I engage in late-night guitar studying. Granted you have a small enough incongruence between your light frequency and string frequency, you'll perceive this incongruence manifesting visually as a stepwise phase-shift of the string vibration at each strobe cycle, which ultimately means that you can fine tune this to visualize a wave with a frequency equal to said incongruence. For a 59Hz monitor like mine, I could visuallize the string as a ~1.5Hz standing wave by playing a Bb2(~116.5Hz). The ruler is just not precise enough and the lighting needs to be very controlled(Preferably the only lightsource present).

Edit: It is very similar in fact to the wave interference which causes you to hear two notes "beat" against eachother when you're tuning.
